Part 1: Memory Architecture & Reference Mechanics
In JavaScript, values are split into Primitive Types (fixed size, direct data copies) and Reference Types (dynamic sizes, memory references) [00:00:44].

Every application utilizes a dual-memory system layout [00:01:41]:

Stack Memory: Stores primitive data values and temporary pointer addresses [00:01:49]. It handles the fast structural operational scopes of your script execution blocks.

Heap Memory: Allocates unstructured, open-ended blocks for larger reference objects (e.g., Arrays, Objects, Functions) [00:02:08].

The Pointer Mechanism
When a reference variable is assigned, the actual large value payload is generated in the Heap [00:02:22]. The named indicator variable inside the Stack holds only a memory pointer address (reference) that targets that heap location [00:02:34].

Shallow Copying Consequences [00:09:15]
Equating one reference object variable to another creates a copy of the pointer reference address inside the Stack, rather than replicating the underlying data payload inside the Heap [00:09:52].

JavaScript
let obj1 = { name: "Love" };
let obj2 = obj1; // Copies the reference pointer address [00:09:10]

obj2.name = "Babbar";
console.log(obj1.name); // "Babbar" (Both variables point to the exact same object space!) [00:09:59]
Part 2: Objects in JavaScript
An Object is a structured, mutable collection of key-value property fields [00:03:30].

Key Constraints: If a property identifier key contains blank spaces, wrap the key inside explicit quotation marks [00:06:24].

JavaScript
let person = {
    name: "Love",
    "full address": "Bhopal, MP", // Quotation marks are mandatory for spaces [00:06:34]
    age: 25,
    // Methods: Functions saved inside an object property [00:07:25]
    greet: function() {
        console.log("Hello ji, kaise ho saare?"); `[00:07:50]`
    }
};

person.greet(); // Calling a saved object method [00:08:06]
Part 3: Arrays in JavaScript
An Array is an ordered list used to hold multiple values sequentially under a single identifier handle [00:10:51]. JavaScript arrays are dynamically sized and can contain a mix of different data types [00:11:16].

A. Core Initialization Options [00:11:21]
JavaScript
// Option 1: Array Literal syntax (Highly Recommended) [00:11:24]
let listA = [1, 2, 3]; 

// Option 2: Array Constructor syntax using the 'new' keyword [00:11:29]
let listB = new new Array("Love", 45, true); `[00:13:14]`
Arrays use Zero-Based Indexing (the first element sits at index 0, the second at 1, etc.) [00:15:12].

B. Built-In Structural Utility Methods
1. Push & Pop (End Management) [00:17:09]
push(value): Appends an element onto the absolute end (right-most edge) of the array [00:17:15].

pop(): Removes and returns the final element from the end of the array [00:17:20].

2. Shift & Unshift (Start Management) [00:18:01]
shift(): Removals the very first element from the start (index 0) of the array [00:18:07].

unshift(value): Injects a new element onto the absolute front of the array, shifting subsequent indices forward [00:18:14].

3. .slice(start, end) [00:18:52]
Extracts a section of an array and returns it as a new array wrapper, excluding the element at the end index [00:20:10].

JavaScript
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Cherry", "Date"];
console.log(fruits.slice(1, 3)); // ["Banana", "Cherry"] (Index 3 is excluded)
4. .splice(start, deleteCount, item1, item2) [00:21:02]
Modifies the contents of an array by removing existing elements and/or adding new elements in place at any index location [00:21:21].

JavaScript
let items = ["Love", "Babbar", "True"];
items.splice(1, 1, "Kunal"); // At index 1, delete 1 item, then insert "Kunal" [00:21:43]
console.log(items); // ["Love", "Kunal", "True"]
5. .sort() & .indexOf(value) [00:37:08]
.sort(): Arranges array values into alphabetical or ascending numeric order in place [00:37:26].

.indexOf(value): Returns the first index where a specified element is found, or -1 if it is not present [00:38:06].

Part 4: Advanced Array Functional Iterators
A. The .map() Method [00:23:01]
Iterates through all array elements, processes them using a callback function, and returns a brand-new array containing the transformed values [00:24:26].

JavaScript
let numbers = [10, 20, 30];
let squares = numbers.map(num => num * num); `[00:24:43]`
console.log(squares); // [100, 400, 900] [00:25:21]
B. The .filter() Method [00:26:34]
Evaluates each element against a conditional test statement. It returns a new array containing only the elements that passed the test (true) [00:27:20].

JavaScript
let mix = [10, 21, 30, 44];
let evens = mix.filter(num => num % 2 === 0); `[00:29:00]`
console.log(evens); // [10, 30, 44] [00:28:44]
C. The .reduce() Method [00:31:22]
Executes a reducer function on each element of the array, combining them into a single aggregate output value [00:31:50].

JavaScript
let costs = [10, 20, 30, 40];
// accumulator acts as the running total; current represents the active element loop
let totalSum = costs.reduce((accumulator, current) => accumulator + current, 0); `[00:33:54]`
console.log(totalSum); // 100 [00:34:22]
Part 5: Specialized Loop Structures
Modern JavaScript introduces cleaner iteration tools to replace standard, verbose for counters [00:40:35]:

forEach Loop: Executes a provided function once for each array element [00:39:06].

JavaScript
numbers.forEach((num, index) => console.log(num, index)); `[00:39:30]`
for-in Loop: Iterates over the keys or property names of an object [00:41:33].

JavaScript
for (let key in person) {
    console.log(key, person[key]); // Outputs keys and their values [00:42:00]
}
for-of Loop: Iterates over the iterable values of an data collection (like arrays or strings) [00:42:38].

JavaScript
for (let value of numbers) {
    console.log(value); // Outputs values: 10, 20, 30 [00:43:17]
}
Part 6: Passing Arrays into Functions
When passing an array into a function, JavaScript passes its reference address pointer rather than copying the entire array data structure [00:44:07].

JavaScript
const calculateSum = (arrayInput) => {
    return arrayInput.reduce((acc, curr) => acc + curr, 0);
};

let userScores = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50];
console.log(calculateSum(userScores)); // Outputs: 150 [00:45:55]